Since you have separate Admin logout and User logout, you must apply the session role remove (session()->forget('role')) in both logout functions.

Because the restriction works using session('role'), so when logout happens you must clear that session.

1----->️⃣ Admin Logout Function

In AdminController

use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Auth;

public function adminLogout()
{
    Auth::logout();  

    session()->forget('role');   // remove role session

    return redirect('/admin/login');
}
2----->️⃣ User Logout Function

In UserController

use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Auth;

public function userLogout()
{
    Auth::logout();

    session()->forget('role');   // remove role session

    return redirect('/login');
}
3----->️⃣ Why This is Important

Example:

Admin login

session('role') = admin

Admin logout → session removed

Now user can login.

If you don't remove session, Laravel will still think:

role = admin

Then user login will be blocked.

4-----> Final Flow
Action	Session
Admin login	role = admin
Admin logout	role removed
User login	role = user
User logout	role removed
5----->Small Tip (Professional way)

Instead of repeating code, you can make one common logout

public function logout()
{
    Auth::logout();
    session()->forget('role');
    return redirect('/');
}

But your separate logout also correct for beginner task.

